Spread¶

Sample Standard Deviation and Variance

S=√∑(X−¯X)2n−1S2=∑(X−¯X)2n−1S=∑(X−X¯)2n−1S2=∑(X−X¯)2n−1

Z-Score:

Z=X−¯XSZ=X−X¯S

Classic¶

Standard Error:

S¯X=S√NSX¯=SN

Degrees of Freedom:

df=N−1df=N−1

Test Statistic:

T=¯X−μ0s¯XT=X¯−μ0sX¯

Standard Error:

s¯Xt=Sw(1−2G)√NG=Proportion trimmed (on each side)sX¯t=Sw(1−2G)NG=Proportion trimmed (on each side)

Degrees of Freedom:

dft=h−1h=N−2⋅⌊G⋅N⌋dft=h−1h=N−2⋅⌊G⋅N⌋

Test Statistic:

Tt=(1−2G)(¯Xt−μ0)Sw√NTt=(1−2G)(X¯t−μ0)SwN

Standard Error (pooled):

S¯X2−¯X1=√S2pn2+S2pn1S2p=(n2−1)S22+(n1−1)S22n2+n1−2SX¯2−X¯1=Sp2n2+Sp2n1Sp2=(n2−1)S22+(n1−1)S22n2+n1−2

Degrees of Freedom:

df=n2+n1−2df=n2+n1−2

Test-Statistic:

T=(¯X2−¯X1)−(μ2−μ1)S¯X2−¯X1T=(X¯2−X¯1)−(μ2−μ1)SX¯2−X¯1

Effect Size: d

d=¯X2−¯X1Spd=X¯2−X¯1Sp

Effect Size: g

g=d⋅(1−34(n1+n2)−9)g=d⋅(1−34(n1+n2)−9)

Standard Error:

dj=(nj−1)S2wjhj(hj−1)hj=nj−2⋅⌊G⋅nj⌋dj=(nj−1)Swj2hj(hj−1)hj=nj−2⋅⌊G⋅nj⌋

Simple Linear Regression¶

(i.e., Linear Regression with one predictor)

Pearson's Correlation Coefficient R:

R=∑(Zx⋅Zy)N−1R=∑(Zx⋅Zy)N−1

Standard Error of R:

SR=√1−R2N−2SR=1−R2N−2

Degrees of Freedom of R:

dfR=N−2dfR=N−2

Slope:

b1=RSySxb1=RSySx

Intercept:

b0=¯Y−b1⋅¯Xb0=Y¯−b1⋅X¯

Slope and Intercept Standard Error:

Sb1=√S2residSSXSb0=√S2resid⋅∑X2iN⋅SSXSb1=Sresid2SSXSb0=Sresid2⋅∑Xi2N⋅SSX

S2resid=∑(Y−^Y)2N−2SSX=∑(Xi−¯X)2Sresid2=∑(Y−Y^)2N−2SSX=∑(Xi−X¯)2

Degrees of Freedom:

df=N−P−1P=The number of predictorsdf=N−P−1P=The number of predictors

Test-Statistics:

Tb1=b1−β1Sb1Tb0=b0−β0Sb0Tb1=b1−β1Sb1Tb0=b0−β0Sb0



Multiple Regression and ANOVA¶

Multiple R-Squared:

R2=SSMSSTR2=SSMSST


Adjusted R-Squared:

R2adj=1−(1−R2)(N−1)N−P−1Radj2=1−(1−R2)(N−1)N−P−1


Total Sum of Squares Formulas (SSTSST):

SST=SSM+SSR=Σ(Yi−¯Ygrand)2=S2grand⋅(N−1)SST=SSM+SSR=Σ(Yi−Y¯grand)2=Sgrand2⋅(N−1)

i=i= individual observations

dfT=N−1dfT=N−1


Model Sum of Squares Formulas (SSMSSM):

SSM=SST−SSR=Σ(^Yi−¯Ygrand)2=Σ nj⋅(¯Yj−¯Ygrand)2SSM=SST−SSR=Σ(Y^i−Y¯grand)2=Σ nj⋅(Y¯j−Y¯grand)2

j=j= number of levels/groups across predictors

dfM=j−1dfM=j−1


Main Effect and Interaction Sum of Squares (SSASSA, SSASSA, SSA×BSSA×B):

SSA=j∑n=1nj⋅(¯Yj−¯Ygrand)2SSA=∑n=1jnj⋅(Y¯j−Y¯grand)2

SSB=j∑n=1nj⋅(¯Yj−¯Ygrand)2SSB=∑n=1jnj⋅(Y¯j−Y¯grand)2

SSA×B=SSM−SSA−SSBSSA×B=SSM−SSA−SSB

j=j= levels/groups within the predictor

dfA=j−1dfB=j−1dfA×B=dfA⋅dfBdfA=j−1dfB=j−1dfA×B=dfA⋅dfB


Residual Sum of Squares Formulas (SSRSSR or SSESSE):

SSR=SST−SSM=Σ(Yi−^Yi)2=Σ(Yij−¯Yj)2=ΣS2j⋅(nj−1)SSR=SST−SSM=Σ(Yi−Y^i)2=Σ(Yij−Y¯j)2=ΣSj2⋅(nj−1)

dfR=dfT−dfMdfR=dfT−dfM


Mean-Squares:

MSx=SSxdfxMSx=SSxdfx


F-stat to Compare Regression Slopes:

F=(N−P−1P)(R21−R2)df1=Pdf2=N−P−1F=(N−P−1P)(R21−R2)df1=Pdf2=N−P−1


F-stat to Compare Two Hierarchical Regression Models:

Fdiff=(N−Pmod2−1Pdiff)(R2diff1−R2mod2)df1=Pdiffdf2=N−Pmod2−1Fdiff=(N−Pmod2−1Pdiff)(Rdiff21−Rmod22)df1=Pdiffdf2=N−Pmod2−1

Effect Size¶

Two Independent Means:¶

Cohen's d:

d=¯x2−¯x1Spd=x¯2−x¯1Sp

Sp=√(n1−1)⋅S21+(n2−1)⋅S22n1+n2−1Sp=(n1−1)⋅S12+(n2−1)⋅S22n1+n2−1


Hedge's g:

g=d⋅(1−34(n1+n2)−9)g=d⋅(1−34(n1+n2)−9)


Two Dependent Means:¶

Cohen's d:

d=¯X1−¯X2Srmd=X¯1−X¯2Srm

Srm=SD√2(1−R)Srm=SD2(1−R)

SD=SD= Standard Deviation of the difference scores.

R=R= Pearson's Correlation Coefficient


Hedge's g:

g=d⋅(1−34(N−1)−1)g=d⋅(1−34(N−1)−1)


ANOVA Main Effects and Interaction¶

Note: A one way ANOVA is just a Two-way ANOVA with a single Main effect and no interaction.

ω2x=SSx−dfx⋅MSRSST+MSRωx2=SSx−dfx⋅MSRSST+MSR

x=x= predictor or interaction


ANOVA Planned Comparisons in terms of R:¶

R=T2T2+dfR=T2T2+df

df=N−P−1df=N−P−1

T=T= The test-statistic for the contrast's bb value.

P=P= the number of predictors (i.e., dummy variables/contrasts)


ANOVA Pairwise Comparisons in terms of D:¶

see Cohen's d for a Two-Sample Independent T-test.



Chi-Square Test¶

χ2=∑(O−E)2Eχ2=∑(O−E)2E

  • O=O= observed frequency

  • E=E= Expected frequency

  • Sum across cells.

Degrees of Freedom for One Variable:

df=k−1df=k−1

k=k= Number of categories.


Expected Frequencies for Two Variables:

Eij=Ri⋅CjNEij=Ri⋅CjN

  • R = row total
  • C = Column total

Degrees of Freedom for Two Variables:

df=(R−1)(C−1)df=(R−1)(C−1)

  • R = Number of rows in the table.
  • C = Number of columns in the table.



Miscellaneous¶

MAD-Median Rule:

|X−median(x)|MADN>2.24|X−median(x)|MADN>2.24


Biserial Correlation:

Rb=Rpb⋅√p⋅quRb=Rpb⋅p⋅qu

  • Rpb=Rpb= Point-Biseral Correlation.
  • p=p= Proportion of cases falling into the largest category.
  • q=q= Proportion of cases falling into the smallest category.

  • u=u= the ordinate (i.e., y-axis value) of a standard normal distribution at pp.

  • Standard Error: SRb=√pqu√NSRb=pquN

  • Test Statistic: ZRb=Rb−ρbSRbZRb=Rb−ρbSRb
